In the 5th century AD, the Western Roman Empire collapsed. The Western Roman Empire failed to adapt for several reasons. First, Germanic tribes like the Visigoths, Ostrogoths, and Vandals invaded the empire. The empire lost land and resources due to poor military defense. Second, the empire had political instability and weak leadership. The frequent emperor changes, military coups, and growth of strong military commanders who frequently operated independently of the central government defined this. The empire struggled to react to foreign challenges and preserve cohesiveness because to political instability. The Western Roman Empire collapsed due to economic and social issues. Complex taxes, high public debt, and wealth concentration hampered the empire. The empire struggled to solve these issues because to administrative and political instability. The Western Roman Empire collapsed owing to military, political, economic, and social issues it couldn't adapt to. 